INSERT INTO `simple_sites` (`id`, `name`, `slug`, `content`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(2, 'he he he he he', 'he-he-he-he-he', '<p>lalalala</p>', '2020-07-30 00:20:38', '2020-07-30 00:20:38'),
(3, 'Forbes', 'forbes', '<p><img alt=\"Why One Entrepreneur Thinks Millions Of Americans Will Spend $25 On His Personalized Shampoo\" src=\"https://thumbor.forbes.com/thumbor/1920x1236/filters%3Aformat%28jpg%29/https%3A%2F%2Fspecials-images.forbesimg.com%2Fimageserve%2F5f3b376e8e4ce51fa797e724%2F0x0.jpg%3Ffit%3Dscale\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>TONY LUONG FOR FORBES</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://www.forbes.com/daily-cover-stories\">DAILY COVER</a>|14.869 views|Aug 18, 2020,06:30am EDT</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://www.forbes.com/sites/amyfeldman/\"><img alt=\"Amy Feldman\" src=\"https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/a64a18b2d15335d7fd6a6e851035b9fa?s=400&amp;d=mm&amp;r=g\" /></a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://www.forbes.com/sites/amyfeldman/\">Amy Feldman</a>Forbes Staff</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://www.forbes.com/manufacturing\">Manufacturing</a></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><strong>Arnaud Plas</strong>&nbsp;is betting on a custom-made machine from France to turn&nbsp;his&nbsp;niche&nbsp;Brooklyn-based&nbsp;hair-care company, Prose,&nbsp;into a&nbsp;beauty behemoth.</h2>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p><strong>Arnaud Plas, the cofounder and CEO of Prose,&nbsp;</strong>is anxiously awaiting the arrival of a 60-foot, 10-ton bespoke machine he has spent two years building. Currently in pieces on a boat somewhere in the middle of the Atlantic, en route to Brooklyn from Normandy, France, the enormous new piece of equipment will let him scale his ultraluxe shampoo company by churning out up to 30,000 custom-mixed bottles a day. Each will cost $25 for 8.5 fluid ounces, around ten times the cost of the equivalent amount of regular old Pantene. If all goes well, it will arrive at the end of August, and he will soon be able to increase the speed of production 30-fold.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Plas thinks he can sell all that pricey shampoo&mdash;and more. Prose is on track to hit $50 million in revenue this year, more than triple last year&rsquo;s figure and above its most optimistic pre-pandemic projections. It also expects to be profitable for the first time next year, helped by a large number of returning customers (55% made repeat purchases in the latest 12 months, far above what Plas says is more typically 30% for the industry). The company, which has raised $25 million in venture funding, is worth an estimated $350 million. &ldquo;We knew that [without the machine] we were a boutique hair-care brand in New York, which was not the ambition of the company,&rdquo; says the 39-year-old Plas, who previously worked at L&rsquo;Or&eacute;al. His ambition, instead, is to get big: to turn his budding shampoo company into a major player in the $850 million high-end hair-care market.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>That&rsquo;s not out of the question. After all, prior to the pandemic, people were already forking over plenty for expensive hair potions from brands like Bumble and Bumble ($25 and up for 8 fluid ounces) and Olaplex ($28 for 8.5 fluid ounces). &ldquo;Prestige hair has been on fire,&rdquo; says NPD Group&rsquo;s Larissa Jensen.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"Prose, custom haircare, haircare, shampoo, beauty, startups, entrepreneurs\" src=\"https://specials-images.forbesimg.com/imageserve/5f3ae5e62de4ea65bc812ee7/960x0.jpg?fit=scale\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>No two alike: Prose figures it can deliver up to 79 trillion possible formulations based on variables like customers&#39; hair type or scalp health and even whether it&rsquo;s sunny or humid where they live.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;<small>TONY LUONG FOR FORBES</small></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Superpremium products are only a sliver of the roughly $13 billion hair-care industry, but the segment has been growing by double digits in recent years and has held steady during the pandemic, while overall beauty sales have tanked. After all, hair flows freely even from behind a mask, and during the lockdown, people have gravitated to little luxuries they can order online.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Plenty could go wrong. There could be problems with Plas&rsquo; machine&mdash;or, like many beauty brands, Prose could simply peter out as the country settles into recession and fickle consumers move on to the next &ldquo;it&rdquo; product.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But Plas, who has spent the better part of his adult life marketing consumer products, is undeterred. A balding man with closely trimmed facial hair, he grew up in southwest France, in a small town called Brive-la-Gaillarde, known for its large food market. His father worked as a production manager at a factory; his mother was an accounting assistant. As a kid, he wanted to open a bakery. &ldquo;I&rsquo;m French,&rdquo; he says with a smile.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Instead, after getting a master&rsquo;s degree in marketing from France&rsquo;s NEOMA Business School, he got a job managing a laundry-detergent brand at German consumer-products giant Henkel. In 2010, he jumped to L&rsquo;Or&eacute;al to oversee Elseve, a top hair-care brand in Europe. By 2014, he was based in New York as L&rsquo;Or&eacute;al&rsquo;s vice president of digital and e-commerce strategy.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"prose\" src=\"https://specials-images.forbesimg.com/imageserve/5f3b08f43407f1daf765f132/960x0.jpg?fit=scale\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p><small>FERNANDO COBELO</small></p>\r\n\r\n<p>That&rsquo;s where he first had the idea to use technology to improve products, rather than simply introduce new ones to grab in-store real estate. &ldquo;We would say, &lsquo;We have a shampoo for dry hair, so why not create a shampoo for v<em>ery&nbsp;</em>dry hair, and it will help increase shelf space with two SKUs at Walmart and Target?&rsquo;&rdquo; Plas says. &ldquo;It&rsquo;s a hamster wheel.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He pitched the idea internally at L&rsquo;Or&eacute;al. &ldquo;They basically told me, &lsquo;Arnaud, you&rsquo;re not here to disrupt the industry,&rsquo;&rdquo; he says.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Frustrated, he left L&rsquo;Or&eacute;al in 2016 and soon decided&nbsp;to start a business customizing shampoos. With Paul Michaux, whom he had first hired as an intern at L&rsquo;Or&eacute;al; Nicolas Mussat, former chief technology officer at real estate firm Meilleurs-Agents; and Catherine Taurin, a top hair chemist in France, he launched Prose in 2017. (Michaux, 30, is now the company&rsquo;s vice president of product, while Mussat, 40, is its chief technology officer, operating out of Paris. Taurin remains an advisor but is not with the startup full-time.)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>After a bit of a false start with off-the-shelf software that proved slow and clunky, Prose built its own version. Based on customers&rsquo; answers to a detailed 25-question online survey, which asks about hair type, scalp health and even Zip code, the software quickly determines the mixture each individual should get. Prose says it can deliver up to 79 trillion possible formulations using more than 160 ingredients, which range from the prosaic (coconut oil) to the exotic (butterfly pea flower). As with any business that relies on data and machine learning, the more customers who complete Prose&rsquo;s questionnaire (so far, more than 2 million have), the more information it has to refine its products. Helping retain those customers is Prose&rsquo;s new subscription business, in which members get 15% off and one-on-one styling tips.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"Prose, custom haircare, shampoo, consumer products, startups, venture capital, haircare\" src=\"https://specials-images.forbesimg.com/imageserve/5f3b0278e91c92fa647ce34e/960x0.jpg?fit=scale\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Three Frenchmen, one vision: Nicolas Mussat, Prose&rsquo;s CTO, and Paul Michaux, its VP of product, cofounded the hair-care brand with CEO Arnaud Plas.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;<small>RUO BING LI</small></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Plas argues that those formulations have helped Prose not only attract customers who might otherwise have shopped at beauty emporiums such as Sephora, but also those who previously bought cheap suds like Pantene. More than half its customers traded up from a mass brand, he says&mdash;a switch he didn&rsquo;t expect and that made him nervous until he saw the repeat numbers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Getting those consumers to keep paying up&mdash;especially if the economic downturn lasts a long time&mdash;will be key to building a larger business. So, too, will Plas&rsquo; hopes for expansion beyond shampoo and conditioner.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He figures the company could move into related areas first (hair color, perhaps) and eventually go further afield (to skin care, maybe, or other beauty categories).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;It doesn&rsquo;t have to be under Prose,&rdquo; Plas says. &ldquo;It could be a new P&amp;G&mdash;a house of personalized brands.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>Follow me on&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.twitter.com/amyfeldman\" target=\"_blank\">Twitter</a>.&nbsp;Send me a secure&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.forbes.com/tips/\" target=\"_blank\">tip</a>.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://www.forbes.com/sites/amyfeldman/\"><img alt=\"Amy Feldman\" src=\"https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/a64a18b2d15335d7fd6a6e851035b9fa?s=400&amp;d=mm&amp;r=g\" /></a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://www.forbes.com/sites/amyfeldman/\">Amy Feldman</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&#39;m a senior editor at Forbes, where I cover manufacturing, industrial innovation and consumer products. I previously spent two years on the Forbes&#39; Entrepreneurs team.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&hellip;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;Read More</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Print</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"mailto:feedback@forbes.com\">Site Feedback</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"https://www.forbes.com/tips/\" target=\"_blank\">Tips</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"mailto:corrections@forbes.com?subject=Report%20Correction:%20Amy%20Feldman&amp;body=Reporting%20Correction%20for:%20%0A%20%0A%20Title:%20Why%20One%20Entrepreneur%20Thinks%20Millions%20Of%20Americans%20Will%20Spend%20$25%20On%20His%20Personalized%20Shampoo%20%0A%20Author:%20Amy%20Feldman%20%0A%20URL:%20https://www.forbes.com/sites/amyfeldman/2020/08/18/why-one-entrepreneur-thinks-millions-of-americans-will-spend-25-on-his-personalized-shampoo/%0A%20%0A%20-%20%0A%20%0A%20Your%20Name:%20%0A%20Correction%20Request:%20%0A%20%0A%20-%20%0A%20%0A%20Thank%20you%20for%20reporting%20a%20correction.%20Forbes%20Staff%20will%20review%20your%20concern%20shortly.\">Corrections</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"https://www.parsintl.com/publication/forbes/\" target=\"_blank\">Reprints &amp; Permissions</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"https://www.forbes.com/terms/\" target=\"_blank\">Terms</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"https://www.forbes.com/fdc/privacy.html\" target=\"_blank\">Privacy</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>&copy; 2020 Forbes Media LLC. All Rights Reserved.</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"https://www.forbes.com/contact/\">Report a Security Issue</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://preferences-mgr.truste.com/?pid=forbes01\">AdChoices</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>8.802 views|Aug 10, 2020,11:20am EDT</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>From Surviving To Thriving: How To Reinvent Your Business After Covid-19 And Beyond</h1>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://www.forbes.com/sites/officedepotofficemax/\"><img alt=\"Office Depot OfficeMax\" src=\"https://blogs-images.forbes.com/assets/images/avatars/blog-7621_400_de74cbb7763d102dc804e727b57e8c42.jpg\" /></a><a href=\"https://www.forbes.com/sites/officedepotofficemax/\">Office Depot OfficeMax</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>BRANDVOICE| Paid Program</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://www.forbes.com/small-business-strategy\">Small Business Strategy</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>When the Covid-19 pandemic hit the United States in early March, the specialty medical services startup Faebris was in the process of renovating a new office space. Given its focus on infectious diseases, with an emphasis on patients with HIV/AIDS whose immune systems are already weakened, the Atlanta-based company knew it needed to move quickly to get its office up and running while also reconsidering how to connect with patients given widespread stay-at-home orders and risks of exposure.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"Focused young businessman holding video call with clients.\" src=\"https://specials-images.forbesimg.com/imageserve/5f296b929cf8e36faa09fa0d/960x0.jpg?fit=scale\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p><small>GETTY</small></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;When everything shut down, we had to really rethink how we would service patients with so many limitations and barriers,&rdquo; says Dr. Zan Tims-Cook, a physician at Faebris.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&rsquo;s a challenge shared by many companies as the pandemic continues to affect the way the world operates, making it imperative that businesses are set up to be agile and ready to shift in step with external forces at a moment&rsquo;s notice. In order to prepare your company for nimble transitions, it&rsquo;s vital to ramp up your technological footprint, rethink your meetings and reevaluate your project management.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Ramp Up Employee Technology</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>To thrive during Covid-19, businesses must rely on technology to bridge the gap created by social distancing and stay-at-home guidelines. With its new office space incomplete and computer-free, Faebris needed to move quickly to implement a digital system that would allow staff to collect and protect critical patient information while also providing patients with the option of virtual consultations whenever possible.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Finding that computers were backordered almost everywhere, Dr. Tims-Cook finally turned to the tech services provider&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.compucom.com/compucom-company-overview\" target=\"_blank\">CompuCom</a>, an Office Depot affiliate company, which quickly set up an in-office computer system complete with the right licenses for securities and compliance that are vital to helping protect private patient information. Patients could now register for appointments online without compromising their privacy. CompuCom also set up a direct service line for Faebris to call at any time of day in case issues came up.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;They implemented things I&rsquo;d never even thought about us needing&mdash;complex systems that they knew would benefit the practice in the long run,&rdquo; said Dr. Tims-Cook.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>While the medical profession has distinct needs, technology is paramount for all companies today, many of which have employees&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.officedepot.com/cm/collections/create-your-space?cm_sp=multi_category-_-ideas-center_category_create-your-space-_-collections_ideas-desktop_main_9_0_0&amp;promo_name=multi_category&amp;promo_id=multi_category-ideas-center-category&amp;promo_creative=ideas-center_category&amp;promo_position=collections_ideas-desktop_main_9_0_0\" target=\"_blank\">working from home</a>&nbsp;and relying on their personal tech to keep daily operations running smoothly. To help remote workers set up an environment equivalent to an in-office environment, consider offering your employees a stipend to purchase products like a WiFi range extender and wireless keyboard to increase productivity levels, for instance. It&rsquo;s also helpful to review your company&rsquo;s cloud storage and internal communications hub to make sure they&rsquo;re optimized for efficiency. For companies without an IT department, or for those that simply need extra hands on deck, Office Depot&rsquo;s&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.officedepot.com/cm/services/tech-services\" target=\"_blank\">Tech Services</a>&nbsp;team provides seamless in-home installation or tech support subscriptions for tech services via phone on the fly.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Rethink Your Meetings</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>With many&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.officedepot.com/cm/article/before-and-after-how-the-workplace-is-changing?cm_sp=marketing-_-ideas-center_before-and-after-how-the-workplace-is-changing_-_-collections_ideas-desktop_main_3_1_0&amp;promo_name=marketing&amp;promo_id=marketing-ideas-center-before-and-after-how-the-workplace-is-changing&amp;promo_creative=ideas-center_before-and-after-how-the-workplace-is-changing&amp;promo_position=collections_ideas-desktop_main_3_1_0\" target=\"_blank\">in-person meetings migrating to video chat</a>, the pandemic is providing businesses with an opportunity to rethink which ones are really necessary and the different ways they can be held in a pandemic-free future. In the case of Faebris, this meant shifting to a partial telemedicine model via a digital health platform&mdash;one they hadn&rsquo;t used before and weren&rsquo;t sure would work.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>While some infections require in-person analysis, said Dr. Tims-Cook, the pandemic allowed her and her colleagues to see that &ldquo;medicine can be practiced in a remote fashion&rdquo;&mdash;a fact that&rsquo;s helpful not just during the current crisis but also as the future unfolds, especially for patients who don&rsquo;t have the time or resources for frequent office visits, for instance. This prompted Faebris to consider an evolved, more efficient way of serving patients.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For other companies, today&rsquo;s challenges could also offer an opportunity to take a step back and reflect on which weekly meetings are truly productive. Those that seem to regurgitate messages and project plans already explained via email might be better kept off the schedule, for example, resulting in more time for employees to focus on daily work and fine-tune their skills. Consolidating the amount of meetings you schedule each week can save time and avoid redundancies, making those you do have more intentional, fruitful and focused on the creative and strategic growth that will benefit the company.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Reevaluate Project Management</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>While working from home can help highlight organizational inefficiencies that may have already existed, it can also exacerbate weaknesses if a company doesn&rsquo;t implement smart solutions. This is especially true when it comes to&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.officedepot.com/cm/article/how-to-quickly-implement-agile-project-management?cm_sp=multi_category-_-ideas-center_curation-article_how-to-quickly-implement-agile-project-management-_-collections_manage-your-people_main_3_44_0&amp;promo_name=multi_category&amp;promo_id=multi_category-ideas-center-curation-article&amp;promo_creative=ideas-center_curation-article&amp;promo_position=collections_manage-your-people_main_3_44_0\" target=\"_blank\">project management</a>, which becomes more imperative when the distractions of home are inevitable&mdash;be it a partner, children or the simple allure of browsing social media. Encouraging your team to stay aware of and on track with approaching deadlines is key to a healthy work-from-home culture.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;As a busy professional, you sometimes want to offload the thinking and doing to someone who can think it through even better than you can,&rdquo; explains Dr. Tims-Cook.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Enter the project manager: If you have one or more on your team already, encourage those staff members to survey employees about what methods work best for staying on top of projects while at home. For companies without project managers or the bandwidth to hire one, consider task-tracking apps that allow all employees to view and update project timelines.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>With the steady flow of in-office conversation on pause, it can also be helpful to have managers institute more regular check-ins via video chat or phone with their direct reports to help prevent some things from getting lost in the shuffle. The result is less employee confusion and increased productivity, leading to a business that&rsquo;s more efficient and collaborative as we work through today&rsquo;s challenges of the pandemic and succeed in the future.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://www.forbes.com/sites/officedepotofficemax/\"><img alt=\"Office Depot OfficeMax\" src=\"https://blogs-images.forbes.com/assets/images/avatars/blog-7621_400_de74cbb7763d102dc804e727b57e8c42.jpg\" /></a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://www.forbes.com/sites/officedepotofficemax/\">Office Depot OfficeMax</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The ODP Corporation (NASDAQ:ODP) is a leading provider of business services, products and digital workplace technology solutions to small, medium and enterprise&hellip;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;Read More</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Print</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"mailto:feedback@forbes.com\">Site Feedback</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"https://www.forbes.com/tips/\" target=\"_blank\">Tips</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"mailto:corrections@forbes.com?subject=Report%20Correction:%20Office%20Depot%20OfficeMax%20Contributor&amp;body=Reporting%20Correction%20for:%20%0A%20%0A%20Title:%20From%20Surviving%20To%20Thriving:%20How%20To%20Reinvent%20Your%20Business%20After%20Covid-19%20And%20Beyond%20%0A%20Author:%20Office%20Depot%20OfficeMax%20Contributor%20%0A%20URL:%20https://www.forbes.com/sites/officedepotofficemax/2020/08/10/from-surviving-to-thriving-how-to-reinvent-your-business-after-covid-19-and-beyond/%0A%20%0A%20-%20%0A%20%0A%20Your%20Name:%20%0A%20Correction%20Request:%20%0A%20%0A%20-%20%0A%20%0A%20Thank%20you%20for%20reporting%20a%20correction.%20Forbes%20Staff%20will%20review%20your%20concern%20shortly.\">Corrections</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"https://www.parsintl.com/publication/forbes/\" target=\"_blank\">Reprints &amp; Permissions</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"https://www.forbes.com/terms/\" target=\"_blank\">Terms</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"https://www.forbes.com/fdc/privacy.html\" target=\"_blank\">Privacy</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>&copy; 2020 Forbes Media LLC. All Rights Reserved.</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"https://www.forbes.com/contact/\">Report a Security Issue</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://preferences-mgr.truste.com/?pid=forbes01\">AdChoices</a></li>\r\n</ul>', '2020-08-19 04:20:29', '2020-08-19 04:22:00');
